### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

platform-browser

### Description

`ApplicationRef.prototype.bootstrap` supports a `rootSelectorOrNode` argument to specify the root element to render the application to. However this argument allows a selector or element incompatible with the selector of the root component.

```typescript
import { Component, ElementRef, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { createApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  template: `
    <!-- Expect this to always be `app-root`. -->
    <div>My tag name is: <code>{{ tagName }}</code>.</div>
  `,
})
export class App {
  private readonly elementRef = inject(ElementRef);
  protected readonly tagName =
    this.elementRef.nativeElement.tagName.toLowerCase();
}

(async () => {
  const root = document.createElement('definitely-not-an-app-root');
  document.body.append(child);

  const appRef = await createApplication();
  appRef.bootstrap(App, root);
})();
```

This works and renders the application into the provided root element, but is also confusing and unexpected that `App` is rendering to a different element than its selector specifies. This makes it easy to accidentally bootstrap an application on the wrong element and I think it breaks the expected invariants of `App`.

The same issues applies with `createComponent` and its `hostElement` property.

https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-hwtnadeo?file=src%2Fmain.ts

### Proposed solution

Throw an error when rendering a component to an element with an incompatible selector.

This goes beyond just tag names, as a component might use attributes or any other syntax in its selector. Ultimately whatever element is provided just needs to match the provided selector. Directives should also receive the same check, though I think that would be harder to abuse.

We can certainly limit this to `ngDevMode` to avoid depending on a runtime representation of the `selector` in production, which I think would be fine.

### Alternatives considered

We can consider that it is actually acceptable for a component to be rendered to an element incompatible with its selector and ignore any complexity or confusion which arises from this.

I don't think it's major problem in urgent need of a fix, but I don't see any valid use case for keeping it around.

